ce:section.ce:para:
The in-situ growth of Mo-Ni3S2 and G-Mo-Ni3S2 were successfully accomplished through the one-step hydrothermal reaction (180 °C, 12 h), in which Ni foam (3 cm × 4 cm) and a mixed (NH4)6Mo7O24·4H2O and CS(NH2)2 solutions were used as precursors (Scheme 1
                     ). There were different amount of GQDs placed in the solution which denoted as Mo-Ni3S2, G-Mo-Ni3S2-1, G-Mo-Ni3S2-2, and so forth. The SEM image of Mo-Ni3S2 is shown in Fig. 1
                     a, which reveals the Mo-Ni3S2 microspheres were grown on the Ni foam. And it is found that the adding amounts of (NH4)6Mo7O24·4H2O has little effect on the morphology of the Mo-Ni3S2. The diameter of Mo-Ni3S2 is about 500 nm and the 3D structure of the pristine Ni foam was well maintained. However, the SEM image of G-Mo-Ni3S2-2 (2 mg GQDs added) displays vertically aligned hierarchical structure with a large surface area which maximizes the exposure of the surface active sites (Fig. 1b). This suggests the crucial role of GQDs in the heterogeneous growth of Mo-Ni3S2 on the Ni foam. At the same time, the morphology of G-Mo-Ni3S2-5 (5 mg GQDs added) is also observed by SEM (Fig. 1c), although the three-dimensional array structure is basically maintained, numerous interconnected agglomerated spherical particles still can be seen on Ni foam surface in some areas, which may be due to poor dispersion of the excessive concentration of GQDs. To further investigate the composition of G-Mo-Ni3S2-2, elemental distribution was revealed by energy-dispersed spectroscopy (EDS) mapping (Fig. S1), which clearly reflect the homogeneous distribution of Ni, Mo, S, and C elements. The general preparation of Mo-Ni3S2 and G-Mo-Ni3S2-2 composites are then characterized by X-ray diffraction. The peaks in the XRD pattern confirm the existence of Ni3S2 and Ni foam (Fig. 1d). The peaks at 21.8°, 31.4°, 38.3°, 49.7°, and 50.1°are assigned to the (101), (101), (003), (113), and (211) planes of Ni3S2 (JCPDS 44-1418) [48,49], while the peaks at 44.5°, 51.8°, and 76.4° are consistent with Ni foam (JCPDS 11-0099). Note that the GQDs loading and Mo atoms doping does not change the crystal structure of Ni3S2. However, from the Fig. S2a, which is the enlarged view of the XRD pattern, by contrast to pure Ni3S2, the diffraction peaks of G-Mo-Ni3S2-2 shifts slightly to a lower angle. These shifts indicate that the lattice parameters of doped Ni3S2 increase due to the larger ion size of Mo than that of Ni. Interestingly, although it is determined from the EDS signals that Mo element totally exist in the G-Mo-Ni3S2-2, no other additional peaks were found in the XRD pattern. In addition, due to the lower content of GQDs, no apparent reflection was obtained.
